\begin_layout Abstract

\size large
As X-FEM approximation doesn't need meshing of the crack, the method has
 garnered a lot of attention from industrial point of view.
 This thesis report summarises some of the concepts involved in Nitsche's
 approach for resolving boundary conditions in embedded interfaces using
 XFEM.
 We consider here cases in which the jump of a field across the interface
 is given, as well as cases in which the primary field on the interface
 is given.
 We will first derive the basics of Nitsche's method and then discretize
 it with X-FEM using shifted basis enrichment.
 We will then implement this on an open source platform, Code-Aster.
\end_layout

