\begin_layout Section
Introduction to the Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to a lot of attention focusing on the development of finite element
 methods for embedded interfaces, currently Nitsche's method has been brought
 forward to enforce constraints, closed form analytical expressions for
 interfacial stabilization terms, and simple flux evaluation by the help
 of works done by Dolbow and others.
 By embedded, we refer to those methods in which the finite element mesh
 is not aligned with the interface geometry (for example X-FEM).
 Because the interfacial geometry can be arbitrary with respect to mesh,
 the robust enforcement of nonlinear constitutive laws(such as frictional
 contact) on embedded interfaces is a challenge that can be tackled with
 the help of Nitsche's method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Focusing on steady problems, but also presenting a case towards time dependent
 problems, the method has been implemented in the open source software Code-Aste
r.
 Two main cases of interface problems have been presented here.
 'Jump' problems, which deal with the interfacial problems concerning those
 in which the jump in the bulk primary (e.g.
 displacement, temperature) and/or secondary (e.g.
 traction, heat flux) field across the interface is known or given.
 The second class of problems are those in which primary field on the interface
 is given, referred to as 'Dirichlet' problems.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The challenge with 'Jump' type of problems, like a perfectly bonded material
 interface in composites, where both jump in displacement and traction across
 the interface vanish, the issue often amounts to the capturing the presence
 of slope discontinuities that arise due to the mismatch in material properties.
 With Nitsche's method, more general case of non-zero jump can also be considere
d, which is more efficient than the enrichment with 'ridge' function and
 simpler to implement than the blending of ramp function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gibbs-Thomson conditions arising in crystal growth and solidification problems,
 where the interfacial temperature is a function of the interfacial velocity
 and curvature, is an example of 'Dirichlet' type of problems.
 The problems associated with such type of situations are usually due to
 unstable Lagrange multipliers even with the most convenient choice.
 Techniques such as penalty methods that may be adequate for enforcing constrain
ts on stationary interfaces often prove to be lacking when it comes to yielding
 accurate, consistent flux quantities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also focus on developing the method taking into consideration some numerical
 issues like high sensitivity of normal flux, mild oscillations and non
 convergence issues.
 To balance this, we propose to calculate a modified numerical flux based
 on a weighted form.
 The advantages of this approach lies firstly in that it is a primal method
 that does not introduce additional degrees of freedom at the embedded interface.
 Secondly, we obtain stabilization parameters that are based on interfacial
 quantities of interest and not necessarily detrimental 'free' parameter.
 Finally on extending the method to problems of contact, Nitsche's method
 yields more accurate approximations of interfacial traction fields.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We implement Nitsche's method focusing on discretization with a shifted
 basis enrichment.
 We also discuss the possibilities of implementing it in a non-linear Newton
 loop and obtain the basic matrix form to do so.
 We will look at an analytical solution and see how the method behaves in
 a simple problem.
 Finally, we will test the method in Code Aster on a circular inclusion
 problem and compare the results with those obtained by using Lagrange multiplie
rs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nitsche's Approach on General boundary condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the simple 2D Poisson problem: find 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\triangle u=f\,\,\,\,\mathrm{{in}}\,\Omega,\label{eq:}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u=u_{0}\,\,\,\,\mathrm{on}\,\Gamma=\partial\Omega_{d},\label{eq:1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial u}{\partial n}=g\,\,\,\,\mathrm{on}\,\Gamma=\partial\Omega_{n}.\label{eq:-9}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a bounded domain with polygonal boundary, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in L^{2}(\Omega)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}\in H^{1/2}(\Gamma)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in L^{2}(\Gamma)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\in\mathrm{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\epsilon\leq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 If we consider the penalty method, by replacing the Dirichlet condition
 with:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\partial u}{\partial n} & = & \frac{1}{\epsilon}\left[(u_{0}-u)+\epsilon g\right]\,\,\,\,\mathrm{on}\,\Gamma,\label{eq:-1}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{\epsilon}\left[u_{0}-u\right]+g\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is a small parameter, which is problem dependent, and n is the outward
 normal.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, the solution to the continuous problem converges to the solution of the
 Dirichlet problem (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1"

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 gives us the pure Neumann condition (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-9"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\epsilon\rightarrow0 & \Rightarrow & u=u_{0}\,\,\,\,\mathrm{on}\,\Gamma\\
u-u_{0} & = & 0\\
\frac{\partial u}{\partial n} & = & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon\rightarrow\infty\Rightarrow\frac{\partial u}{\partial n}=g\,\,\,\,\mathrm{on}\,\Gamma
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The drawbacks of this method are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
nonconformity - the method requires coupling of the penalty parameter to
 the mesh size
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
possible ill conditioning of the discrete system when 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is too small 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider the variational form of the above simple problem.
 Multiply (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:"

\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V_{h}$
\end_inset

, integrating over the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, and using Green's formula, leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\nabla u_{h},\nabla v)_{\Omega}-(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{\Gamma}=(f,v)_{\Omega}\label{eq:-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now multiply the boundary condition (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-1"

\end_inset

) by 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and integrating over the domain which gives,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{\Gamma}+\frac{1}{\epsilon}(u_{h},v)_{\Gamma}=\frac{1}{\epsilon}(u_{0},v)_{\Gamma}+(g,v)_{\Gamma}\label{eq:-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adding (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-2"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-3"

\end_inset

), the problem is equivalent to finding 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{h}\in V_{h}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\nabla u_{h},\nabla v)_{\Omega}\cancel{-(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{\Gamma}}\cancel{+(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{\Gamma}}+\frac{1}{\epsilon}(u_{h},v)_{\Gamma}=(f,v)_{\Omega}+\frac{1}{\epsilon}(u_{0},v)_{\Gamma}+(g,v)_{\Gamma}\,\,\,\,\forall v\in V_{h}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\nabla u_{h},\nabla v)_{\Omega}+\frac{1}{\epsilon}(u_{h},v)_{\Gamma}=(f,v)_{\Omega}+\frac{1}{\epsilon}(u_{0},v)_{\Gamma}+(g,v)_{\Gamma}\,\,\,\,\forall v\in V_{h}\label{eq:-8}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following Juntenen and Stenberg formulations
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-1"

\end_inset

, consider, for simplicity, a regular shaped finite element partitioning
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{h}$
\end_inset

) of the domain (
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subset\text{R}^{N}$
\end_inset

) into triangles or tetrahedra have been considered.
 The induced mesh is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}_{h}$
\end_inset

, on the boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $K\in\mathcal{T}_{h}$
\end_inset

 denotes the element of the mesh with diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}$
\end_inset

 denotes the edge or face with diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Further definition consists of
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h:=\text{max}\left\{ h_{K}:K\in\mathcal{T}_{h}\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{h}:=\left\{ v\in H^{1}\left(\Omega\right):v_{|K}\in\mathcal{P}_{p}\left(K\right)\,\,\,\,\forall K\in\mathcal{T}_{h}\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{p}(K)$
\end_inset

 is the space of polynomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Integrating (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-3"

\end_inset

) over an element 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 now gives us:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{E}+(u_{h},v)_{E}=(u_{0},v)_{E}+\epsilon(g,v)_{E}\label{eq:-4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 We can write now (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-4"

\end_inset

) as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\{ \epsilon(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{E}+(u_{h},v)_{E}\right\} =\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\{ (u_{0},v)_{E}+\epsilon(g,v)_{E}\right\} \label{eq:-5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a positive parameter, known as the stability parameter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-3"

\end_inset

), we can write, by multiplying the condition with 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial v}{\partial n}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}+(u_{h},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}=(u_{0},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}+\epsilon(g,\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly like (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-5"

\end_inset

), we can write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}-\frac{\gamma h_{E}}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\{ \epsilon(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}+(u_{h},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}\right\} =\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}-\frac{\gamma h_{E}}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\{ (u_{0},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}+\epsilon(g,\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}\right\} \label{eq:-6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adding (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-2"

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-5"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-6"

\end_inset

), we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
(\nabla u_{h},\nabla v)_{\Omega}-(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{\Gamma} & + & \sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\{ \epsilon(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{E}+(u_{h},v)_{E}\right\} 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}-\frac{\gamma h_{E}}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\{ \epsilon(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}+(u_{h},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
=(f,v)_{\Omega}+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\{ (u_{0},v)_{E}+\epsilon(g,v)_{E}\right\} +\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}-\frac{\gamma h_{E}}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\{ (u_{0},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}+\epsilon(g,\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{h}\in V_{h}$
\end_inset

 such that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{B}_{h}(u_{h},v)=\mathcal{F}_{h}(v)\,\,\,\,\forall v\in V_{h}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{B}_{h}(u,v) & = & (\nabla u,\nabla v)_{\Omega}\\
 &  & +\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\left\{ -\frac{\gamma h_{E}}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left[\left\langle \frac{\partial u}{\partial n},v\right\rangle _{E}+\left\langle u,\frac{\partial v}{\partial n}\right\rangle _{E}\right]+\frac{1}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\langle u,v\right\rangle _{E}-\frac{\epsilon\gamma h_{E}}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\langle \frac{\partial u}{\partial n},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n}\right\rangle _{E}\right\} \nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{F}_{h}(v) & = & (f,v)_{\Omega}\label{eq:-7}\\
 &  & +\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\left\{ \frac{1}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\langle u_{0},v\right\rangle _{E}-\frac{\gamma h_{E}}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\langle u_{0},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n}\right\rangle _{E}+\frac{\epsilon}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\langle g,v\right\rangle _{E}-\frac{\epsilon\gamma h_{E}}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\langle g,\frac{\partial v}{\partial n}\right\rangle _{E}\right\} \nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use Nitsche's technique at the limiting condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=0$
\end_inset

.
 This method can also be extended to the whole range of boundary conditions,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we put 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-7"

\end_inset

), we can see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
(\nabla u_{h},\nabla v)_{\Omega}-(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{\Gamma} & + & \sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\epsilon+\cancel{\gamma h_{E}}}\left\{ \epsilon(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{E}+(u_{h},v)_{E}\right\} 
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cancel{+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}-\frac{\gamma h_{E}}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\{ \epsilon(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}+(u_{h},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}\right\} }
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
=(f,v)_{\Omega}+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\epsilon+\cancel{\gamma h_{E}}}\left\{ (u_{0},v)_{E}+\epsilon(g,v)_{E}\right\} +\cancel{\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}-\frac{\gamma h_{E}}{\epsilon+\gamma h_{E}}\left\{ (u_{0},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}+\epsilon(g,\frac{\partial v}{\partial n})_{E}\right\} }
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\nabla u_{h},\nabla v)_{\Omega}\cancel{-(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{\Gamma}}\cancel{+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}(\frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v)_{E}}+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\epsilon}(u_{h},v)_{E}=(f,v)_{\Omega}+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\epsilon}(u_{0},v)_{E}+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}(g,v)_{E}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\nabla u_{h},\nabla v)_{\Omega}+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\epsilon}(u_{h},v)_{E}=(f,v)_{\Omega}+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\epsilon}(u_{0},v)_{E}+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}(g,v)_{E}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the same as the traditional form obtained in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-8"

\end_inset

) with .
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0,$
\end_inset

 the system may become ill-conditioned at small 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a stabilized method with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0,$
\end_inset

 at the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=0,$
\end_inset

 we get the Dirichlet problem with Nitsche's application: find 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{h}\in V_{h}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
(\nabla u,\nabla v)_{\Omega}-\left\langle \frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},v\right\rangle _{\Gamma}-\left\langle u_{h},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n}\right\rangle _{\Gamma} & +\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\gamma h_{E}}\left\langle u_{h},v\right\rangle _{E}\nonumber \\
=(f,v)_{\Omega}-\left\langle u_{0},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n}\right\rangle _{\Gamma} & +\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\gamma h_{E}}\left\langle u_{0},v\right\rangle _{E} & \forall v\in V_{h}\label{eq:-10}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

and at 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\rightarrow\infty,$
\end_inset

 it is a pure Neumann problem that needs to be solved: find 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{h}\in V_{h}$
\end_inset

 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\nabla u,\nabla v)_{\Omega}+\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\gamma h_{E}\left\langle \frac{\partial u_{h}}{\partial n},\frac{\partial v}{\partial n}\right\rangle _{E}=(f,v)_{\Omega}+(g,v)_{\Gamma}-\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\gamma h_{E}\left\langle g,\frac{\partial v}{\partial n}\right\rangle _{E}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This requires that the data satisfy
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(f,1\right)_{\Omega}+\left\langle g,1\right\rangle _{\Gamma}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and this condition is not violated in the above formulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparison with other approaches
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the governing equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\nabla\centerdot(\kappa\nabla u)=f\,\,\,\,\mathrm{{in}}\,\Omega,\label{eq:-22}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u=u_{0}\,\,\,\,\mathrm{on}\,\Gamma=\partial\Omega\label{eq:1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We will now discuss some techniques to weakly impose Dirichlet constraints
 on embedded surfaces and try to develop one method from another while briefly
 discussing the merits of one over the other.
 This part is based on the work done by Sanders, Dolbow and Laursen.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 the unit normal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 which points out of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 The primal variable of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is defined in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{U},$
\end_inset

 and its variation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta u$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{U}_{0}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{U}=\left\{ u\in H^{1}(\Omega),u=u_{0}\,\mathrm{on}\,\Gamma\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{U}_{0}=\left\{ u\in H^{1}(\Omega),u=0\,\mathrm{on}\,\Gamma\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

The potential energy of such a system can be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi(u)=\frac{1}{2}\int_{\Omega}\nabla u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Omega}fu\mathrm{d}\Omega
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 minimizes this potential energy under Dirichlet constraints.
 We can transform this constrained problem into an unconstrained one by
 using Lagrange multipliers.
 For the constraint to be enforced, let's build the Lagrangian of the system,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

, by adding the work of the Lagrange multipliers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{L}=H^{-1/2}(\Gamma^{*})$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{L}(u,\lambda) & = & \Pi(u)+\int_{\Gamma}\lambda(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\int_{\Omega}\nabla u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Omega}fu\mathrm{d}\Omega+\int_{\Gamma}\lambda(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 We get a dual variational formulation due to the stationarity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(\delta u,\delta\lambda)\in\mathbb{U}_{0}\times\mathbb{L}$
\end_inset

 find 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,\lambda)\in\mathbb{U\times L}$
\end_inset

, such that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta\mathcal{L}=\int_{\Omega}\nabla\delta u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Omega}\delta uf\mathrm{d\Omega}+\int_{\Gamma}\lambda\delta u\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta\lambda(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align right

\shape italic
(Lagrangian method)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 cannot be independently determined.
 And this brings about a lot of stability issues.
 We can solve this by the use of penalty methods.
 We can interpret Lagrange multipliers as flux imposed on the boundary condition.
 This leads us to establish 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=-\kappa\nabla u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}$
\end_inset

, the flux.
 Now we assume that the flux can be approximated in a spring like form 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\nabla u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\approx-\epsilon(u-u_{0}).$
\end_inset

 The penalty potential is now, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi^{\mathrm{pen}}(u) & = & \Pi(u)+\int_{\Gamma}\frac{\epsilon}{2}(u-u_{0})(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\nonumber \\
 & = & \Pi(u)+\int_{\Gamma}\frac{\epsilon}{2}(u-u_{0})^{2}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\int_{\Omega}\nabla u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Omega}fu\mathrm{d}\Omega+\int_{\Gamma}\frac{\epsilon}{2}(u-u_{0})^{2}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primal penalty variational form is given by: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta u\in\mathbb{U}_{0}$
\end_inset

 find 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\mathbb{U}$
\end_inset

, such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta\Pi^{\mathrm{pen}}=\int_{\Omega}\nabla\delta u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Omega}\delta uf\mathrm{d\Omega}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta u\epsilon(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align right

\shape italic
(Penalty method)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is not variationally consistent, as the desired problem is solved only
 in the limiting case when 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another standard way to improve the behavior of a Lagrangian method is to
 stabilize it with a penalty term.
 This gives the augmented Lagrangian approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{L}^{\mathrm{aug}}(u,\lambda) & = & \Pi(u)+\int_{\Gamma}\lambda(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\frac{\epsilon}{2}(u-u_{0})^{2}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\int_{\Omega}\nabla u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Omega}fu\mathrm{d}\Omega+\int_{\Gamma}\lambda(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\frac{\epsilon}{2}(u-u_{0})^{2}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here the penalty stiffness can be seen as the stabilization parameter, which
 does not need large values of it.
 The dual variational form: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(\delta u,\delta\lambda)\in\mathbb{U}_{0}\times\mathbb{L}$
\end_inset

 find 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,\lambda)\in\mathbb{U\times L}$
\end_inset

, such that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta\mathcal{L}^{\mathrm{aug}} & = & \int_{\Omega}\nabla\delta u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Omega}\delta uf\mathrm{d\Omega}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta u\lambda\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta\lambda(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta u\epsilon(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\nonumber \\
 & = & \int_{\Omega}\nabla\delta u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Omega}\delta uf\mathrm{d\Omega}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta u(\lambda+\epsilon(u-u_{0}))\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta\lambda(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}=0
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align right

\shape italic
(Augmented Lagrangian method)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the same manner to obtain a penalty variational form from a Lagrangian
 one, we can utilize the flux relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=-\kappa\nabla u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the potential function that forms the basis of Nitsche's method.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Pi^{\mathrm{Nit}}(u) & = & \Pi(u)-\int_{\Gamma}(u-u_{0})\kappa\nabla u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\frac{\epsilon}{2}(u-u_{0})^{2}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{2}\int_{\Omega}\nabla u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Omega}fu\mathrm{d}\Omega-\int_{\Gamma}(u-u_{0})\kappa\nabla u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\frac{\epsilon}{2}(u-u_{0})^{2}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We get one-field symmetric variational formulation: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta u\in\mathbb{U}_{0}$
\end_inset

 find 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\mathbb{U}$
\end_inset

, such that :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta\Pi^{\mathrm{Nit}}(u) & = & \int_{\Omega}\nabla\delta u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Omega}\delta uf\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Gamma}\delta u\kappa\nabla u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\nonumber \\
 &  & -\int_{\Gamma}(u-u_{0})\kappa\nabla\delta u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta u\epsilon(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}=0
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align right

\shape italic
(Nitsche's method)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging, we can write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{\Omega}\nabla\delta u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Gamma}\delta u\kappa\nabla u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}-\int_{\Gamma}(u-u_{0})\kappa\nabla\delta u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta u\epsilon(u-u_{0})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}=\int_{\Omega}\delta uf\mathrm{d\Omega}
\]

\end_inset

or:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{\Omega}\nabla\delta u\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}-\int_{\Gamma}\delta u\kappa\nabla u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}-\int_{\Gamma}u\kappa\nabla\delta u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta u\epsilon u\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
= & \int_{\Omega}\delta uf\mathrm{d\Omega}- & \int_{\Gamma}u_{0}\kappa\nabla\delta u\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\Gamma}\delta u\epsilon u_{0}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\label{eq:-11}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we compare this with (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-10"

\end_inset

), we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is similar to the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{E\in\mathcal{G}_{h}}\frac{1}{\gamma h_{E}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Application to Interfaces
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Application-on-Interface"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now extend Nitsche's method to an interface made of two materials
 or even to a crack that divides the surface.
 We develop this based on the works of Dolbow and Harari.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-2"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Find 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in\mathbb{U}$
\end_inset

, such that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{b}(v,u)+a_{i}(v,u)=l_{b}(v)+l_{i}(v)\,\,\,\,\forall v\in\mathbb{U}_{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where now:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{b}(v,u)=\int_{\Omega}\nabla v\centerdot\kappa\nabla u\mathrm{d\Omega}
\]

\end_inset

and: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
l_{b}(v)=\int_{\Omega}vf\mathrm{d\Omega}
\]

\end_inset

are the standard bulk contributions from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-11"

\end_inset

), with: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbb{U}_{\,\,} & = & \left\{ u\in H^{1}(\Omega^{-}\cup\Omega^{+}),u=u_{0}\,\mathrm{on}\,\Gamma,\mbox{ may be discontinuous on }\mathcal{S}\right\} \mbox{ and}\\
\mathbb{U}_{0} & = & \left\{ v\in H^{1}(\Omega^{-}\cup\Omega^{+}),v=0\,\mathrm{on}\,\Gamma,\mbox{ may be discontinuous on }\mathcal{S}\right\} .
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}(v,u)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{i}(v)$
\end_inset

 are the interfacial contributions which depend on the case being considered.
 These terms are obtained by utilizing the boundary conditions in a similar
 manner to that in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-11"

\end_inset

), but on the interface, if we can consider the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 to be divided by an interface 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph*
Dirichlet condition (ex.
 crack surface)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the boundary conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u^{+}=g^{+},\,\,\,\,u^{-}=g^{-}\mbox{\,\,\,\,\ on }\mathcal{\mathcal{S}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-}$
\end_inset

 are assumed to be sufficiently smooth functions of the position on the
 interface.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{-}$
\end_inset

 are limiting values of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 as the interface is approached from either 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{+}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Approaching this problem as two one-sided problems, we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
a_{i}(v,u) & = & a_{i}(v,u)^{+}+a_{i}(v,u)^{-}\label{eq:-15}\\
l_{i}(v) & = & l_{i}(v)^{+}+l_{i}(v)^{-}\label{eq:-16}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We choose the interfacial normal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}$
\end_inset

 as pointing outwardly from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{+}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives us, from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-11"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
a_{i}(v,u)^{+} & = & -\int_{\mathcal{S}}v^{+}(\kappa^{+}\nabla u^{+}\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}-\int_{\mathcal{S}}u^{+}(\kappa^{+}\nabla v^{+}\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\mathcal{S}}v^{+}\alpha^{+}u^{+}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\label{eq:-17}\\
a_{i}(v,u)^{-} & = & -\int_{\mathcal{S}}v^{-}(\kappa^{-}\nabla u^{-}\centerdot\left(-\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\right))\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}-\int_{\mathcal{S}}u^{-}(\kappa^{-}\nabla v^{-}\centerdot\left(-\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\right))\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\mathcal{S}}v^{-}\alpha^{-}u^{-}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\nonumber \\
 & = & \int_{\mathcal{S}}v^{-}(\kappa^{-}\nabla u^{-}\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\mathcal{S}}u^{-}(\kappa^{-}\nabla v^{-}\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\mathcal{S}}v^{-}\alpha^{-}u^{-}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\label{eq:-42}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
l_{i}(v)^{+} & = & -\int_{\mathcal{S}}g^{+}(\kappa^{+}\nabla v^{+}\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\mathcal{S}}v^{+}\alpha^{+}g^{+}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\label{eq:-43}\\
l_{i}(v)^{-} & = & -\int_{\mathcal{S}}g^{-}(\kappa^{-}\nabla v^{-}\centerdot\left(-\mathrm{\mathbf{n}}\right))\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\mathcal{S}}v^{-}\alpha^{-}g^{-}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\nonumber \\
 & = & \int_{\mathcal{S}}g^{-}(\kappa^{-}\nabla v^{-}\centerdot\mathrm{\mathbf{n}})\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}+\int_{\mathcal{S}}v^{-}\alpha^{-}g^{-}\mathrm{d}\mathrm{\Gamma}\label{eq:-44}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where we have chosen 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{-}$
\end_inset

 as the stabilization parameters for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{+}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-}$
\end_inset

 domains respectively (Figure 
