\begin_layout Subsection
Exact numerical solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here the bar is divided by an interface at 
\begin_inset Formula $y=a$
\end_inset

.
 All horizontal movements are restricted, thus letting us simplify the given
 problem into a 1D bar problem.
 The entire bar is made of a single material with Young's modulus 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 We assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, Poisson's ratio, to be zero.
 From equilibrium equations, we have, in the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{+}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underbar{\mbox{div}}\,\underline{\underline{\sigma}}=\boldsymbol{0}
\]

\end_inset

Integrating the equilibrium equation gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{\underline{\sigma}}=A\boldsymbol{e_{y}}\otimes\boldsymbol{e_{y}}
\]

\end_inset

or:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sigma & = & A\\
E\varepsilon & = & A
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Integrating again gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=\frac{1}{E}\left(Ay+B\right)
\]

\end_inset

From boundary conditions we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
u(y=H) & = & 0\\
0 & = & AH+B
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and also:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(y=a^{+})=\frac{1}{E}\left(Aa+B\right)
\]

\end_inset

In the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{-}$
\end_inset

, we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underbar{\mbox{div}}\,\underline{\underline{\sigma}}=\boldsymbol{0}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{\underline{\sigma}}=C
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=\frac{1}{E}\left(Cy+D\right)
\]

\end_inset

Applying the boundary conditions gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
u\left(y=0\right) & = & 0\\
0 & = & D
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and also:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(y=a^{-})=\frac{1}{E}\left(Ca\right)
\]

\end_inset

From the condition of jump in the stress at the interface, we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{j}(y=a)=A-C=0
\]

\end_inset

and jump in displacement:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mbox{i}(y=a) & = & \frac{1}{E}\left(Aa+B\right)-\frac{1}{E}\left(Ca\right)\\
2gE & = & Aa+B-Ca
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=2Eg
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=-\frac{2E}{H}g
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=-\frac{2E}{H}g
\]

\end_inset

and: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D=0
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=-\frac{2E}{H}g\,\,\,\,\mbox{in}\,\Omega^{+}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=-\frac{2g}{H}y+2g\,\,\,\,\mbox{in}\,\Omega^{+}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=-\frac{2E}{H}g\,\,\,\,\mbox{in}\,\Omega^{-}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=-\frac{2g}{H}y\,\,\,\,\mbox{in}\,\Omega^{-}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

