\begin_layout Subsection
Circular Inclusion problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this two-dimensional bi-material test case, a weak discontinuity is present,
 and the displacement field is continuous with discontinuous stresses and
 strains.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-7,key-11"

\end_inset

 Inside a circular plate of radius b, whose material is defines by 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=0.25$
\end_inset

, a circular inclusion with radius 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 of different material with 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}=10$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0.3$
\end_inset

 is considered.
 The loading of the structure results from a linear displacement of the
 outer boundary: 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{r}\left(b,\theta\right)=r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\theta}\left(b,\theta\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The situation is depicted in figure (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Problem-statement-of"

\end_inset

).
 The exact solution can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-16"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Doc2.pdf
	BoundingBox 170bp 470bp 430bp 715bp
	clip

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Problem-statement-of"

\end_inset

Problem statement of the circular inclusion problem (the gray area is the
 numerical domain)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The stresses are given as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{rr}\left(r,\theta\right)=2\mu\varepsilon_{rr}+\lambda\left(\varepsilon_{rr}+\varepsilon_{\theta\theta}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{\theta\theta}\left(r,\theta\right)=2\mu\varepsilon_{\theta\theta}+\lambda\left(\varepsilon_{rr}+\varepsilon_{\theta\theta}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the Lamé constants 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 have to be replaced by the appropriate values for the corresponding area,
 respectively.
 The strains are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{rr}\left(r,\theta\right)=\begin{cases}
\left(1-\frac{b^{2}}{a^{2}}\right)\alpha+\frac{b^{2}}{a^{2}}, & 0\le r\le a\\
\left(1+\frac{b^{2}}{r^{2}}\right)\alpha-\frac{b^{2}}{r^{2}}, & a\le r\le b
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon_{\theta\theta}\left(r,\theta\right)=\begin{cases}
\left(1-\frac{b^{2}}{a^{2}}\right)\alpha+\frac{b^{2}}{a^{2}}, & 0\le r\le a\\
\left(1+\frac{b^{2}}{r^{2}}\right)\alpha-\frac{b^{2}}{r^{2}}, & a\le r\le b
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the displacements:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{r}\left(r,\theta\right)=\begin{cases}
\left[\left(1-\frac{b^{2}}{a^{2}}\right)\alpha+\frac{b^{2}}{a^{2}}\right]r, & 0\le r\le a\\
\left(r-\frac{b^{2}}{r^{2}}\right)\alpha+\frac{b^{2}}{r}, & a\le r\le b
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{\theta}\left(r,\theta\right)=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 involved in these definitions is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha=\frac{\left(\lambda_{1}+\mu_{1}+\mu_{2}\right)b^{2}}{\left(\lambda_{2}+\mu_{2}\right)a^{2}+\left(\lambda_{1}+\mu_{1}\right)\left(b^{2}-a^{2}\right)+\mu_{2}b^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the numerical model, the domain is a square of size 
\begin_inset Formula $L\times L$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $L=2$
\end_inset

, the outer radius is chosen to be 
\begin_inset Formula $b=2$
\end_inset

 and the inner radius 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0.4$
\end_inset

.
 The exact stresses are prescribed along the boundaries of the square domain,
 and displacements are prescribed as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{1}\left(0,\pm1\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

and:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{2}\left(\pm1,0\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

Plane strain conditions are assumed.
 Results are obtained for different methods, Nitsche's method, penalty method
 and non-linear method with Lagrange multipliers.
 A set of displacement and stress on gauss points plots have been presented
 in figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Circular-inclusion-problem"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Circular-inclusion-problem-4"

\end_inset

.
 The interface is embedded into the mesh and Code Aster divides every element
 cut by the interface into sub-elements.
 The elements adjacent to the ones cut by interface are also enriched.
 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Circular-inclusion-problem-2"

\end_inset

).
 The displacement plot shows a continuous change of the magnitude in both
 the axis(figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Circular-inclusion-problem-3"

\end_inset

), while the stress plot shows the discontinuous stress in the two domains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We compare the error norms by considering linear irregular, linear regular,
 quadratic irregular, qudratic regular and triangular irregular elements.
 Note that in quadratic elements, the shape functions assume a quadratic
 nature.
 (Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Relative-energy-norm-1-1-1"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Relative-energy-norm-1-1-1-1"

\end_inset

) The convergence order is the highest for a structured grid with quadratic
 shape functions.
 This is obvious as better approximation is obtained with higher order of
 polynomial.
 On comparison with other methods like penalty and lagrange multipliers
 (figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Relative-energy-norm-1-1-1-3"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Relative-energy-norm-1-1-1-4"

\end_inset

), we see that Nitsche's method has slightly better convergence than penalty
 method.
 But we have seen from the previous example that we need to prescribe very
 high penalization parameter to obtain this resulting in higher conditioning
 of the system.
 Nitsche's method is competitive on comparison to Lagrange method but comes
 free of additional degree of freedom associated with Lagrange multipliers.
